04408nam a22005415i 9780773596733DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735967337 a10.1515/97807735967332doi  a(DE-B1597)655502  a(OCoLC)881860210  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a335.4112211 aDel Noce, Augusto, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Crisis of Modernity /cCarlo Lancellotti, Augusto Del Noce. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Studies in the History of Ideas ;v6400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTranslator's Introduction -- tModernity, Revolution, Secularization -- tThe Idea of Modernity -- tViolence and Modern Gnosticism -- tRevolution, Risorgimento, Tradition -- tThe Latent Metaphysics within Contemporary Politics -- tSecularization and the Crisis of Modernity -- tThe Advent of the Technocratic Society -- tToward a New Totalitarianism -- tThe Shadow of Tomorrow -- tThe Death of the Sacred -- tThe Roots of the Crisis -- tThe Ascendance of Eroticism -- tThe Predicament of the West -- tAuthority versus Power -- tA “New” Perspective on Right and Left -- tThe Story of a Solitary Thinker -- tNotes on Secularization and Religious Thought -- tEric Voegelin and the Critique of the Idea of Modernity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn his native Italy Augusto Del Noce is regarded as one of the preeminent political thinkers and philosophers of the period after the Second World War. The Crisis of Modernity makes available for the first time in English a selection of Del Noce's essays and lectures on the cultural history of the twentieth century. Del Noce maintained that twentieth-century history must be understood specifically as a philosophical history, because Western culture was profoundly affected by the major philosophies of the previous century such as idealism, Marxism, and positivism. Such philosophies became the secular, neo-gnostic surrogate of Christianity for the European educated classes after the French Revolution, and the next century put them to the practical test, bringing to light their ultimate and necessary consequences. One of the first thinkers to recognize the failure of Marxism, Del Noce posited that this failure set the stage for a new secular, technocratic society that had taken up Marx’s historical materialism and atheism while rejecting his revolutionary doctrine. Displaying Del Noce's rare ability to reconstruct intellectual genealogies and to expose the deep metaphysical premises of social and political movements, The Crisis of Modernity presents an original reading of secularization, scientism, the sexual revolution, and the history of modern Western culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilization, Modern. 0aSecularization. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aLancellotti, Carlo, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311127407208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014z978311127709740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077359673340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773596733423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773596733/original  a978-3-11-127407-2  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  a978-3-11-127709-7  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles